title: For Sale/Trade:  WWII 2nd contract Astra 600/43 9mm Parabellum
postcontent:
I have a WWII produced 9mm Parabellum (Luger)Astra 600/43 for sale or trade. These pistols were contracted to Spain for the Nazi military. Approx. 60,000 were produced, but due to the Allied invasion of France, only the first 10,500 were delivered to the Germans. The rest of them ended up in storage until the end of the war. After WWII, the West German government needed to arm the police, and remembered the pistols in Spain. The Spanish forced them to repurchase them, even though the Nazi government had already paid for them . In effect, these guns were purchased twice. This pistol was made in 1944, with a 26xxx serial number. It comes with two original magazines and a issue holster. The gun fires standard 9mm Luger, and is in great mechanical condition. All serial numbers match, the mags are not numbered. There is slight holster wear on the high spots, but less than you would commonly expect for a gun of it's age. 85 to 90 % original bluing. No import marks. The bore is mirror bright. It is an accurate, well made pistol. Holster has faint "Geco" makers mark. A interesting piece of WWII history, and a good shooter.
Outright sale price is $475.00
I am interested in trades for other handguns, military bolt action rifles (mauser, enfield, etc) modern rifles, shotguns, or just about anything. Please feel free to send trade offers, I love to deal.

postcontent:
I am a bullet collector, I have a thing for rare bullets and interesting head stamps. Interested in nazi stampings, Chinese/ nap stampings and/or single rounds. Sorry but I'm not buying a box of ammo I only need one of to put in my display case unless the whole box is the same price I would pay for just one bullet. Also interested in Arabic or other non English lettering head stamps or any stamps that are from hostile armies. 


Of course still interested in american/NATO rounds I don't yet have in my collection. Wildcat cartridges, need a 5.6x28, 300winmag, 300 blackout, 456 rigby. 458SOCOM, any of the 500 rounds.

I also want to complete my collection of .22 caliber rounds. 

Just because its common doesnt mean I have it, there's no order to what I have so if you have a spare round or 2 and don't have the gun anymore and would take a few dollars for it offer it, I'm not gonnahi peoples :) 
i need some advice please, 
my partner wants to try sounding and i have no idea what to do. 
Ive never tried it before and can not find much info on the net except places to buy sounds, but we have already purchased one. 
we have got a van buren dilator set. 

is there any tips that people could give me on what to do, i know that you need to use a lot of lube (we have a good quality one) 
and the equipment needs to be serialized . 
the only way i know how to serialize objects is by boiling them, but i am unsure if this would be the correct thing to do with sounds . 

i have also read that if you are going to try something on someone to try it on yourself first, but i have the same problem of not knowing what im doing and i do know that male and female sounds are different shapes, well i have read anyway. 
please help 
kindest regards Kylie
 care if you offer something I already have so shoot me all offers. 

Please don't offer me your collection, my son and I do this together and it's no fun to buy a complete collection.  Not saying I won't buy multiple rounds from one person, but last time I posted this I had a few people offer my their entire collection already in a nice display for hundreds of dollars, that's the only thing I'm not interested in.

title: For Sale/Trade:   1st Yr./Only Year 1955 High Standard Sentinel .22 w/ 5" Barrel
postcontent:
Extremely rare 1955 High Standard Sentinel 9 shot double action .22 revolver with the 5" barrel! This is the ONLY year that these great shooting Alloy Framed 'Kit' Guns were produced in this barrel length, so not many available.
 Also; this one has the early indexing system soon dropped by the bean counters in favor of a less costly method of manufacture, & so has a smoother action than later years.
 This is a fun little revolver that is very light, and fires almost like an auto!
It is very accurate too! 
 The grips were based on the Colt Pocket guns of the 19th Century and were called 'the most comfortable grip' since the Civil War'.
 I've seen this model go for big money, but this one is 'well broken in' & is priced accordingly. it has the usual scuffs from the early style springless ejector, and wear consistent with it's age, but shoots perfectly & never shaves lead.
 If you are looking for something rare, exotic, & fun- let me know. I can send details & pics.
